    likes/matches/messages/calls/storage aren't built — all of which
    contradicted work already verified live since 2026-07-06→10). Rather
    than build against an unverified prose doc, wrote
    `app doctumant/BACKEND_SCHEMA_VERIFICATION_QUESTIONS.md` asking for the
    actual migration SQL + clarifications. Backend responded confirming:
    `profiles_viewed_count`/`profiles_viewed_reset_at` and `notify_safety_*`
    columns exist but have no consumer yet (flagged not-safe-to-use);
    `is_suspended` etc. exist but nothing sets them (no admin flow yet); the
    likes/matches/messages/calls/storage "Next Steps" claim was confirmed
    stale, not a regression; Google OAuth unconfirmed, still don't build
    against it; and `fcm_tokens`' unique constraint is genuinely on `token`
    alone (not composite `(user_id, token)`), kept that way deliberately,
    with an explicit offer to switch if asked.
  - User asked to request the switch to `(user_id, token)` (safer — a
    token-alone constraint means a reused/reissued token could silently
    reassign an existing row to a different user_id on upsert). That ask is
    a follow-up to send back to backend; NOT yet changed on their end.
  - Client-side change made now, independent of that follow-up (works
    correctly against either constraint shape): `fcm_service.dart` — new
    `_registerToken()` upserts `{user_id, token, platform, updated_at}` onto
    `fcm_tokens` (`onConflict: 'token'`, matching the constraint as it
    stands today) whenever a token is first obtained or refreshes; new
    public `registerTokenForCurrentUser()` re-attempts the write, called
    from `auth_controller.dart`'s `signIn()`/`signUp()` success paths in
    case a token was already obtained before the user signed in (fire-and-
    forget via `unawaited`, doesn't block the auth flow or its state
    transition).
  - Result / verification: flutter analyze -> same 4 pre-existing unrelated
    lint-style infos, nothing new. flutter test -> All tests passed (2,
    unchanged). Not run on-device — still needs a real login on a physical/
    emulated device with Play services to confirm a row actually lands in
    `fcm_tokens`.
  - Open items / follow-ups: send the `(user_id, token)` constraint-change
    ask back to backend; once `fcm_tokens` is populated for real users,
    backend's dispatcher Edge Function (still unconfirmed whether it exists
    — see BACKEND_SCHEMA_VERIFICATION_QUESTIONS.md §3.4) is the remaining
    piece before a push notification can actually reach a device.

