  `mock_data.dart`'s 5-tier plan list updated to match the user's real
  pricing table exactly — also corrected Premium Elite's profile/likes cap
  from the old placeholder 2,000 to the real 2,500.
- **`Profile` model** — new `planId` field (`profiles.plan_id`, proposed
  column, read-only from the client — only `verify-purchase` sets it
  server-side, never a direct client PATCH). Read via `fromJson`, excluded
  from `toInsertJson`/`updateMyProfile` on purpose.
- **`isPremiumProvider` — found and fixed a real wiring gap while building
  this.** It was a bare `StateProvider<bool>` defaulting to `false`,
  completely disconnected from the real, already-live
  `profiles.is_premium` column — the old mock subscription flow's
  "activation" was just flipping this local flag, and every premium gate
  across Discover/Likes/Profile/Settings read only from it, never from the
  real column. Now a derived `Provider<bool>` reading
  `currentUserProvider`'s `isPremium` — same 5 call sites (Discover,
  Likes, Profile, Settings, Subscription) work unchanged since they only
  ever did `ref.watch(isPremiumProvider)` (a plain bool read), but now
  backed by real data instead of a settable mock.
- **`lib/core/billing/billing_service.dart`** (NEW) — thin wrapper around
  `InAppPurchase.instance`: `isAvailable()`, `queryProducts()` (throws
  `ProductNotFoundException` if a Play Console listing is missing),
  `buySubscription()`, `completePurchase()`, `restorePurchases()`,
  exposes `purchaseStream`. Never verifies a purchase itself — that
  requires the Google Play Developer API server-side only.
- **`lib/shared/data/purchase_repository.dart`** (NEW) —
  `SupabasePurchaseRepository.verifyPurchase()` invokes a proposed
  `verify-purchase` Edge Function with `{plan_id, product_id,
  purchase_token}`, expects `{plan_id, premium_until}` back. Maps a 404 to
  `PurchaseFeatureUnavailableException` ("not available yet"), any other
  non-2xx to `PurchaseVerificationException` (surfaces the backend's own
  `message`).
- **`subscription_screen.dart` — rewritten for real billing.** On init,
  subscribes to `purchaseStream` (once, held for the widget's lifetime)
  and queries live Play prices for all 5 products (falls back to the
  static USD price display if a listing isn't found/live yet — common
  during development before Play Console propagation). Each non-current
  plan card gets a real "Subscribe" button (only rendered once product
  query resolves) that launches the actual Play purchase sheet. Purchase
  results arrive asynchronously via the stream: a `purchased`/`restored`
  status triggers `verifyPurchase()`, and — regardless of verification
  outcome — always calls `completePurchase()` afterward, since an
  unacknowledged purchase is re-delivered by the Billing Library on every
  app start otherwise (would otherwise retry a permanently-rejected
  purchase forever). On verified success, invalidates `currentUserProvider`
  so the real plan/premium status shows immediately. The renewal banner
  and "CURRENT" plan ribbon now read the real `Profile.planId`/
  `premiumUntil` instead of a hardcoded `'gold'`/"Gold Plan" string.
- Android: added `com.android.vending.BILLING` permission to
  `AndroidManifest.xml` — required for `BillingClient` to connect at all;
  build would have silently failed to find any products without it.
- Verified: `flutter analyze` → same baseline (8 infos, all pre-existing
  style, zero new — clean across all new billing code). `flutter test` →
  All tests passed (2, unchanged). `flutter build apk --debug` → BUILT
  successfully (Play Billing library compiles alongside Agora/ML
  Kit/Firebase natives with no conflicts). Not run on-device — needs a
  real Play Console listing with the 5 products configured, a signed
  build uploaded to at least an internal-testing track, and a real backend
  `verify-purchase` function to exercise the full purchase→premium round
  trip meaningfully (Google Play Billing does not work against debug/
  unsigned builds side-loaded outside the Play Store).
- **New `app doctumant/BACKEND_PAYMENTS_HANDOFF.md`** — full backend
  contract: the `profiles.plan_id` column, the `verify-purchase` Edge
  Function (exact request/response shape, the Google Play Developer API
  verification steps including the easy-to-miss "must acknowledge the
  purchase within ~3 days or Google auto-refunds it" requirement, a
  recommended `purchases` table for token-replay-across-accounts
  prevention), and Real-Time Developer Notifications (RTDN) as a
  recommended-but-not-blocking follow-up for renewals/cancellations/
  refunds (flagged clearly: without it, a user who cancels via the Play
  Store directly will keep `is_premium=true` until their `premium_until`
  naturally lapses, since nothing else re-verifies on a schedule).
- **FINAL TIER status: client-side billing integration fully built,
  blocked on backend shipping §1 (schema) + §2 (Edge Function) before any
  real purchase can be verified and premium actually granted.** This
  closes out the last item on the original A/B/C/Final tier list — every
  planned feature area has now had a frontend pass; remaining known gaps
  are the pre-existing ones (zero real test coverage, Android release
  signing, the unanswered schema-verification thread) plus whatever
  backend delivers/flags in response to this doc.

2026-07-15 — GIT CORRUPTION WORKAROUND + FULL SESSION PUSHED. The original
`love_me` working copy's `.git/objects/` had genuine NTFS-level corruption
(an object-directory entry reporting an impossible 8.8-exabyte size with
garbage timestamps) that made every `git add`/`hash-object -w` targeting
certain hash prefixes fail with "unable to create temporary file: Invalid
argument" — not a git bug, a filesystem-level fault, confirmed via `stat`
showing a nonsensical inode/size/link-count for the offending path.
`chkdsk /f /r` was the real fix but too slow to run mid-session; instead,
cloned the repo fresh into a sibling `love_me_fresh` folder (clean `.git`,
same `origin/main` history), copied the entire working tree over via
`robocopy`, re-verified `flutter analyze`/`test` passed identically in the
clone, removed one thing that shouldn't have been swept in (a 169KB stale
Kotlin build-cache folder, `build_stale_20260710181644/`, added a
`build_stale_*/` `.gitignore` rule), and committed+pushed the entire
session's work (A-TIER through FINAL TIER, ~155 files) to `origin/main` as
a single commit (`f091f38`). `love_me_fresh` is now the working copy of
record; the original `love_me` folder's `.git` corruption was left
unrepaired (user's call whether to `chkdsk` it later or just delete it).

