2026-07-15 — BACKEND ANSWERED THE SCHEMA-VERIFICATION QUESTIONS (sent
2026-07-11, previously unanswered — this closes that loose end).
`app doctumant/Schema Verification Response.md` covers `profiles`,
`active_sessions`, `fcm_tokens`, `user_presence`, plus 3 general/process
questions, with the actual `create table` SQL for each rather than prose.
Cross-checked every flagged item against the actual client code before
assuming anything needed fixing:
- **`profiles`** — confirmed all the previously-disputed columns
  (`photo_verification`, `is_suspended`/etc., `profiles_viewed_count`/etc.,
  `notify_safety_*`) are real and live, not aspirational; an earlier
  client-side doc (`migration_001.md`) was the one that was wrong/
  incomplete. Backend explicitly said NOT to build against
  `profiles_viewed_count`/`profiles_viewed_reset_at` (dead columns — real
  quota enforcement is `get_view_quota()`/`record_profile_view()`) or
  `notify_safety_*`/`is_suspended`/etc. (schema-only, nothing reads/writes
  them yet, no admin tooling exists). Grepped the client: confirmed **zero
  references to any of these columns anywhere in `lib/`** — nothing to
  fix, already compliant with backend's guidance by virtue of never having
  built against speculative schema.
- **`active_sessions`** — backend found and fixed a real bug on their own
  side (a trigger referencing a column that didn't exist yet, silently
  erroring every heartbeat `UPDATE` — now fixed via `024_active_sessions_
  updated_at_fix.sql`, no client action needed). Backend also asked
  whether `registerSession()`'s "always insert a new row" behavior was
  intentional (their schema supports both "one row per device" and "one
  row per login event" models) — verified against
  `device_session_repository.dart`/`device_session_registrar.dart`: this
  was **already a deliberate, already-documented design choice**
  ("only call it once per actual sign-in... the row itself is
  intentionally left... a history of this device's past sessions"), not
  an oversight. No change needed, just confirmed intentional.
- **`fcm_tokens`** — backend flagged a **required client change**: the
  unique constraint changed from global `token` to `(user_id, token)`,
  meaning `onConflict: 'token'` would error post-migration. Checked
  `fcm_service.dart`: **already correctly using `onConflict:
  'user_id,token'`** — this was already fixed in an earlier session, nothing
  to do.
- **`user_presence`** — confirmed no staleness sweep exists server-side
  (a real, acknowledged gap — a crashed/killed client can show "online"
  indefinitely). Backend offered a client-side mitigation (derive "online"
  from `last_seen` recency rather than trusting `is_online` blindly) as a
  stopgap until a server-side sweep exists — **not implemented this
  session**, flagged as a possible future improvement to `presence_repository.dart`/
  wherever presence is displayed, not urgent enough to block on.
- **Google Sign-In** — backend could not confirm from their repo alone
  whether the OAuth provider is actually configured in the live Supabase
  dashboard (no `[auth.external.google]` in `config.toml`, but dashboard-only
  config wouldn't show there). Client's `signInWithGoogle()` already exists
  and calls `signInWithOAuth(OAuthProvider.google)`, unchanged — backend's
  recommendation was "don't assume this works," not "fix the client code,"
  so nothing to change; just noting the risk that tapping "Sign in with
  Google" in the live app may currently fail silently/error until backend
  confirms the provider is enabled with a real client ID.
- **Net result: zero client code changes required.** Every item backend
  flagged as needing a fix was already correctly handled in the current
  codebase (either from an earlier session's work, or because the client
  never touched the schema-only/dead columns in the first place). This
  response closes out the "unanswered schema-verification thread" item
  that had been sitting on the known-gaps list since 2026-07-11.
